<subSubSection id="C2DF6529F321FFEFFF15FB27FE0260E9" pageId="24" pageNumber="23" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8A7A36A2F321FFEFFF15FB27FE0260E9" blockId="24.[192,1439,1182,1238]" pageId="24" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis id="B8B1EAB0F321FFEFFF15FB27FEC26089" bold="true" box="[192,347,1182,1206]" pageId="24" pageNumber="23">Etymology.</emphasis>
This species is named for the Tilarán mountain range in 
<collectingCountry id="F2D27632F321FFEFFBD6FB27FB1E6089" box="[1027,1159,1182,1206]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="24" pageNumber="23">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
, where the Monteverde locality is located.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C2DF6529F321FFEFFF15FB54FED26159" pageId="24" pageNumber="23" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8A7A36A2F321FFEFFF15FB54FED26159" blockId="24.[192,1440,1261,1382]" pageId="24" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis id="B8B1EAB0F321FFEFFF15FB54FED6613A" bold="true" box="[192,335,1261,1285]" pageId="24" pageNumber="23">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species is distinguished from other 
<taxonomicName id="4DC54D21F321FFEFFC88FB57FC3F6139" authorityName="Jacoby" authorityYear="1881" box="[861,934,1262,1286]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Beltia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B8B1EAB0F321FFEFFC88FB57FC3F6139" box="[861,934,1262,1286]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="23">Beltia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the combination of a uniform bright metallic green head, prothorax, and elytra, with legs, pterothorax, and abdomen orangish brown. In all other metallic green 
<taxonomicName id="4DC54D21F321FFEFFE14FA97FD936179" authorityName="Jacoby" authorityYear="1881" box="[449,522,1326,1350]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Beltia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B8B1EAB0F321FFEFFE14FA97FD936179" box="[449,522,1326,1350]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="23">Beltia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the thorax and at least the base of the abdomen are the same color as the dorsal side.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C2DF6529F321FFEFFF15FAC7FC9D6188" pageId="24" pageNumber="23" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8A7A36A2F321FFEFFF15FAC7FC9D6188" blockId="24.[192,1440,1406,1463]" pageId="24" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis id="B8B1EAB0F321FFEFFF15FAC7FEDA61A9" bold="true" box="[192,323,1406,1430]" pageId="24" pageNumber="23">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species has been collected only from Monteverde and surrounding localities in the Tilarán mountain range of 
<collectingCountry id="F2D27632F321FFEFFDD9FA26FD166188" box="[524,655,1439,1463]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="24" pageNumber="23">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="12FE2A27F321FFEFFD4AFA26FD6E6188" box="[671,759,1439,1463]" captionStart="Figures 80–82" captionStartId="44.[192,286,1848,1870]" captionTargetBox="[203,1427,215,1809]" captionTargetId="figure@44.[203,1429,211,1815]" captionTargetPageId="44" captionText="Figures 80–82. Distribution maps for Beltia spp.: Nicaragua, Costa Rica, and Panama. 80) Beltia angustomarginata (squares), B. osa (triangles), B. vacilona (circles). 81) Beltia chiriquensis (circles), B. herreri (stars), B. nicaraguensis (hexagons). 82) Beltia sanchezae (square), B. tilarana (inverted triangles), B. tisingalita (stars)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3713529" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3713529/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="23">Fig. 82</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
